Test your new short code or long code Messaging channel to ensure that itâ€™s working the way you expect. Using a sandbox is optional, but a good idea.

This article applies to: Standard and enhanced SMS channels. It doesn't apply to Messaging for In-App, Messaging for Web, standard and enhanced WhatsApp, standard and enhanced Facebook Messenger, enhanced Apple Messages for Business, and Bring Your Own Channel.

To create an SMS channel in either sandbox or production, you must file a case with Salesforce Support. When you file the case, we recommend requesting separate numbers for sandbox and production.

Salesforce Support can move a number from a standard SMS channel in sandbox to a standard SMS channel in production. However, using separate numbers makes your channel rollout easier and gives you more freedom to experiment in your sandbox org in the future.

Test your channel in sandbox or production:

* Set up Messaging in your sandbox.
* Complete the steps in Get Started with Messaging in Service Cloud.
* Test your channel by sending a text message from your phone.
* Look for the incoming message in Omni-Channel and exchange messages.
* When you're done, click End Chat.

If you need to move your SMS channel implementation or number from sandbox to production, follow these steps:

* Create a change set to move your Messaging implementation from sandbox to production.
* If you couldn't designate a separate number for your sandbox, file a case with Salesforce Customer Support to move the number to a new channel in production.
title: Testing Service Cloud SMS Channels
